                                <date>1958</date>. С. <biblScope unit="page">??–??</biblScope>.</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><encodingDesc><tagsDecl>&amp;renditions;</tagsDecl></encodingDesc></teiHeader><text><body><entry xml:id="entry_kærkæ-mærkæ" xml:lang="os"><form type="lemma"><orth>kærkæ-mærkæ</orth></form><sense><sense><tr xml:lang="ru"><q>яркий</q></tr><tr xml:lang="en"><q>bright</q></tr></sense><sense><tr xml:lang="ru"><q>пестрый</q></tr><tr xml:lang="en"><q>many-coloured</q></tr></sense><sense><tr xml:lang="ru"><q>расцвеченный</q></tr><tr xml:lang="en"><q>coloured</q></tr></sense></sense><etym xml:lang="ru">Для первой части ср. <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><lang/> <w>kärk</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="trk"><w>körk</w> <gloss><q>красота</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><w>körkü</w> <gloss><q>прекрасный</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><w>kärkäi</w> <gloss><q>быть украшенным</q></gloss></mentioned>,  (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Радлов"/><biblScope>II 1098, 1259–1261</biblScope></bibl>). Вторая часть (%imærkæ%i) представляет не имеющий самостоятельного значения ассонанс к первой, как в <ref type="xr" target="#entry_qūlon-mūlon"/> ‘пестрый’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kʼæʒ-mæʒ"/> ‘кривой’ и т. п. (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_РОСл."/><biblScope>611–612</biblScope></bibl>).</etym><etym xml:lang="en">For a first part cf. <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><lang/> <w>kärk</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="trk"><w>körk</w> <gloss><q>beauty</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><w>körkü</w> <gloss><q>beautiful</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="trk"><w>kärkäi</w> <gloss><q>to be decorated</q></gloss></mentioned>,  (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Радлов"/><biblScope>II 1098, 1259–1261</biblScope></bibl>). The second part (%imærkæ%i) is a vocalic alliteration of the first part, which has no individual meaning, the same way as in <ref type="xr" target="#entry_qūlon-mūlon"/> ‘many-coloured’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kʼæʒ-mæʒ"/> ‘crooked’ etc. (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_РОСл."/><biblScope>611–612</biblScope></bibl>).</etym></entry></body></text></TEI>